<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-appreciation" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Appreciation</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.4 Commercial Arithmetic
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                        Determine the value of appreciation and depreciation of assets
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To conceptualize the real-world meaning of asset appreciation and discover how to calculate percentage increase based on an initial principal value.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Organize learners into diverse groups of <m>2-4</m>. Circulate around the room to ensure groups differentiate between assets that grow in value (like land) and those that lose value (like vehicles). Guide them gently through the percentage calculations without explicitly revealing the compound appreciation formula.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>
        <activity>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <term>Work in Groups to:</term>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Identify and record in the table the items in your surrounding environment that increase in value over time. Discuss the factors that contribute to the increase in value of these items.
                </p>
                <tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" right="medium" left="medium">
                    <row header="yes">
                        <cell>Item</cell>
                        <cell>Factor Contributing to increase in value</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Land</cell>
                        <cell>Infrastructure Development</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>?</cell>
                        <cell>?</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>?</cell>
                        <cell>?</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>?</cell>
                        <cell>?</cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
                <p>
                    <alert>In your Groups Explore the question below;</alert>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Dr. Lucian Talu Mabayi bought a piece of land in Kisumu and Nairobi at Ksh <m>2,000,000</m> and Ksh <m>6,000,000</m> respectively. After <m>1</m> years, the land in Kisumu is now worth Ksh <m>2,600,000</m> while the land in Nairobi is worth Ksh <m>6,600,000</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>In your groups</alert> you are required to;
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Find the increase in value for each piece of land. 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Compare the increase to identify which piece of land increased more in value.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Find the percentage increase in value for each piece of land.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Based on your results, discuss in your groups:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(i)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                How can you express the increase in value using the original value and the new value?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                How can you express the increase as a fraction of the original value?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                How can this fraction be written as a percentage?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Further Exploration:</alert> If the land continues to appreciate at the same rate every year, find the value after the second year and the third year.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalize group findings into the generalized multi-year appreciation formula, making connections to compound interest structures.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Connecting to Learner Work:</alert> Highlight the Kisumu vs. Nairobi land problem. Show learners that while both plots grew by an absolute value of Ksh <m>600,000</m>, the Kisumu plot had a higher percentage rate of appreciation (<m>30\%</m> vs <m>10\%</m>). This demonstrates why percentages are used to compare financial growth equitably.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Algebraic Transition:</alert> Lead the class through factoring out the principal <m>P</m> to move from <m>P + \frac{R}{100}P</m> to the factored form <m>P\left(1 + \frac{R}{100}\right)</m>, then logically extend this exponentiation to year <m>T</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>
    <insight>
        <p>
            The increase in value of an asset over time is referred to as <term>Appreciation</term>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Let the original value of the land be <m>P</m>, the new value be <m>A</m>, the increase in value be <m>I</m>, and the percentage increase be <m>R</m>. 
        </p>
        <p>
            From the learner experience, we can see that,
        </p>
        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow> A = \amp \; P + I </mrow>
                <mrow> I = \amp \; \frac{R}{100} \times P </mrow>
                <mrow> A = \amp \; P + \frac{R}{100} \times P </mrow>
                <mrow> = \amp \; P \left(1 + \frac{R}{100}\right) </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            For the second year the new value becomes the original value.
        </p>
        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow> A = \amp \; P \left(1 + \frac{R}{100}\right) + \frac{R}{100} \times P \left(1 + \frac{R}{100}\right) </mrow>
                <mrow> = \amp \; P \left(1 + \frac{R}{100}\right) \left(1 + \frac{R}{100}\right) </mrow>
                <mrow> = \amp \; P \left(1 + \frac{R}{100}\right)^2 </mrow>
            </md>
            
        </p>
            <p>
                In general, after <m>T</m> years, the value of the asset can be calculated using the formula, <me>A = P \left(1 + \frac{R}{100}\right)^T</me>
            </p> 
    </insight>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A piece of land in a developing suburban area is purchased for <m>2,500,000</m> Shillings. If the value of land in that area appreciates at a steady rate of <m>15\%</m> per annum, what will be the value of the land after <m>6</m> years?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <alert>Identify the given values</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> P \amp =\; 2,500,000 \;\ text{shillings} </mrow>
                    <mrow> R \amp = \; 15 \% </mrow>
                    <mrow> T \amp = \;  6\;\text{years}</mrow>
                    <mrow> A \amp = \; ? </mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                Apply the Appreciation formula, <m> A = P(1 + R)^T</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> A \amp =\; 2,500,000 (1 + \frac{15}{100})^6 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \;2,500,000 \times 2.31306 = 5,782,650 \text{ Shillings}</mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <title>Finding the Original Value (Principal)</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A company's current value is <m>4,200,000</m> Shillings. It has been appreciating at a rate of <m>8\%</m> per year for the last <m>5</m> years. How much was the original value?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <alert>Identify the given values:</alert>
                <md>
                    <mrow> A \amp =\; 4,200,000 \text{ Shillings} </mrow>
                    <mrow> R \amp = \; 8\% \text{ p.a.} </mrow>
                    <mrow> T \amp = \; 5 \text{ years} </mrow>
                    <mrow> P \amp = \; ? </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Make <m>P</m> the subject in the appreciation formula: 
                <me>P = \frac{A}{\left(1 + \frac{R}{100}\right)^T}</me>
            </p>
            <p>
                Substitute the values into the adjusted formula:
                <md>
                    <mrow> P \amp = \; \frac{4,200,000}{\left(1 + \frac{8}{100}\right)^5} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \; \frac{4,200,000}{(1.08)^5} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \; \frac{4,200,000}{1.46933} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp \approx \; 2,858,448 \text{ Shillings} </mrow>
                </md>
                The original value of the company 5 years ago was approximately <m>2,858,448</m> Shillings.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <title>Calculating the Annual Appreciation Rate</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A house was bought for <m>120,000</m> Shillings and sold <m>10</m> years later for <m>311,200</m> Shillings. At what annual rate did the house appreciate?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <alert>Identify the given values:</alert>
                <md>
                    <mrow> P \amp =\; 120,000 \text{ Shillings} </mrow>
                    <mrow> A \amp = \; 311,200 \text{ Shillings} </mrow>
                    <mrow> T \amp = \; 10 \text{ years} </mrow>
                    <mrow> R \amp = \; ? </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Rearrange the appreciation formula to solve for <m>R</m>:
                <md>
                    <mrow> \frac{A}{P} \amp = \; \left(1 + \frac{R}{100}\right)^T </mrow>
                    <mrow> \sqrt[T]{\frac{A}{P}} \amp = \; 1 + \frac{R}{100} </mrow>
                    <mrow> R \amp = \; 100 \times \left( \sqrt[T]{\frac{A}{P}} - 1\right) </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Substitute the given values into your derived equation:
                <md>
                    <mrow> R \amp = \; 100 \times \left(\sqrt[10]{\frac{311,200}{120,000}} - 1\right)</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \; 100 \times \left(\sqrt[10]{2.59333} - 1\right)</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \; 100 \times ((1.1000) - 1)</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \; 10\% \text{ per annum}</mrow>
                </md>
                The house appreciated at an annual rate of <m>10\%</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

